WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.860
And I'm excited. We have two Waldenstroms talks in one session for such a rare disease. That's

00:00:04.860 --> 00:00:10.980
really exciting. So I'm going to be presenting data. This is actually from my colleague,

00:00:11.440 --> 00:00:17.920
Jorge Castillo at our center. This is his trial that we've been enrolling patients on. So I'll

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:23.840
give you an update on this. And so as we just heard, there are many therapies available for

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:30.580
Waldenstroms. But the issue is with a lot of our therapies are indefinite or patients don't achieve

00:00:30.580 --> 00:00:36.280
really deep responses. And so we're trying to improve on that with this trial. So we used

00:00:36.280 --> 00:00:42.020
Pertabrutinib and Venetoclax. Those are both known to be safe and effective in Waldenstroms.

00:00:42.300 --> 00:00:46.600
The downside to those agents, so Pertabrutinib, as I just mentioned, is one of those indefinite

00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:52.700
therapies. And Venetoclax, the original trial, the treatment was for two years. But then when

00:00:52.700 --> 00:00:53.820
treatment was stopped, about half a year later, it was gone. And so we're trying to improve on

00:00:53.820 --> 00:01:00.440
half of patients relapse by six months. So many of us give that indefinitely or have that high

00:01:00.440 --> 00:01:05.480
risk of relapse pretty quickly. So although those are both available and they work well,

00:01:05.500 --> 00:01:12.260
we're trying to improve on that. And we know that the combination of BTK inhibitors and BCL2

00:01:12.260 --> 00:01:18.140
inhibitors generally are safe in other diseases. This trial was kind of a follow-up to our prior

00:01:18.140 --> 00:01:23.800
trial that was Ibrutinib and Venetoclax, which was stopped due to high cardiac toxicity.

00:01:23.800 --> 00:01:27.960
With multiple patients who had ventricular arrhythmias. So we're very cautious and

00:01:27.960 --> 00:01:34.820
careful with this study using this combination. And luckily, knock on wood somewhere, we have

00:01:34.820 --> 00:01:40.140
not seen any issues with that in Waldenstroms so far with Pertabrutinib.

00:01:41.520 --> 00:01:47.720
So again, this is Foriacus Dios trial investigator initiated multi-center phase two trial. This is

00:01:47.720 --> 00:01:53.320
in patients who were previously treated for Waldenstroms. They had to have had

00:01:53.780 --> 00:01:59.220
a BT or they had to have had one line of therapy before. And what we were looking for in this trial

00:01:59.220 --> 00:02:06.720
was the VGPR and CR rate. As mentioned before, many of our therapies have higher overall response

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:11.860
rates, but the depth of response is quite limited. With Venetoclax alone, only about 20% of patients

00:02:11.860 --> 00:02:19.040
achieve a VGPR or CR. With the BTK inhibitors, it's about 20 to 30% of patients. So we designed

00:02:19.040 --> 00:02:23.760
the trial with this statistical plan, as you can see, with an alternative hypothesis of greater

00:02:23.760 --> 00:02:29.980
than or equal to 35% VGPR or CR. And the null hypothesis, when we made this plan, would be

00:02:29.980 --> 00:02:34.900
rejected if 12 or more patients achieved that. And you'll see in this data I'm about to present

00:02:34.900 --> 00:02:39.600
that even with only partial enrollment of the trial at the time of this data collection,

00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:46.020
we had met that endpoint. So the key inclusion criteria, adult patients with Waldenstroms

00:02:46.020 --> 00:02:52.680
who needed therapy and that had one treatment before. Initially, we allowed patients that were

00:02:52.680 --> 00:02:53.740
mid-88 negative.

00:02:53.740 --> 00:03:00.120
In the trial, we had two patients who were treated, and unfortunately, both of them relapsed

00:03:00.120 --> 00:03:05.900
pretty quickly. So then we modified the trial to only include mid-88 positive patients after that

00:03:05.900 --> 00:03:13.420
point. And you can see the treatment schedule below. So her tabrutinib is started on day one

00:03:13.420 --> 00:03:18.580
and given as a single agent for the first month. And during month two, Venetoclax is ramped up

00:03:18.580 --> 00:03:23.720
on a weekly schedule of 100, 200, and then 400 milligrams, with glucomycin, which is a

00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:27.360
single agent for the first month. And then, as I mentioned, we've had close TLS monitoring, and we

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:30.900
haven't had any significant TLS.

00:03:30.900 --> 00:03:37.700
So the baseline characteristics, as expected with Waldenstroms, a median age of 69, mostly males.

00:03:37.700 --> 00:03:44.300
Prior therapies in this trial was a median of one. About half of the patients had had a prior

00:03:44.300 --> 00:03:51.720
covalent BTKI exposure. And of those patients that were exposed, most of them were resistant to

00:03:51.720 --> 00:03:53.700
covalent BTK inhibition.

00:03:53.700 --> 00:04:00.500
The T4 rate was pretty close, slightly higher than the typical rate at 44%, and 19% of patients had

00:04:00.500 --> 00:04:07.680
a TP53 mutation.

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:13.780
So here you can see the responses with a median follow-up of 11 months. 55% of patients had

00:04:13.780 --> 00:04:18.940
achieved a VGPR or CR, so we're seeing pretty deep responses. This is even, you know, patients

00:04:18.940 --> 00:04:23.680
that were not completing the two years of treatment yet, and we were already seeing these deep

00:04:23.680 --> 00:04:28.800
responses. We have now completed enrollment in this trial, and I'll say we're continuing to see

00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:35.040
similar outcomes now with all of the patients enrolled in the trial.

00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:40.240
We can see that there's a difference in response to therapy, though, as you see here. So these are

00:04:40.240 --> 00:04:46.940
the patients that achieved a VGPR or CR. That's the burgundy color, and then the blue is patients

00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:53.660
who achieved less than a VGPR. So based on prior BTK inhibitor exposure, you can see that there's

00:04:53.660 --> 00:04:58.860
less than a VGPR, and we can see those who had had a previous BTK inhibitor are less likely to achieve

00:04:58.860 --> 00:05:03.780
a deep response. Some of these are not statistically significant because of small numbers at the time

00:05:03.780 --> 00:05:09.080
of this analysis, but I wonder if they will ultimately be statistically significant when we

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:14.700
look at all of the patients enrolled. We also saw a difference for those who had a CXCR4 mutation,

00:05:15.240 --> 00:05:21.320
less likely to achieve a VGPR, and the same thing with those patients who had a TP53 mutation.

00:05:23.640 --> 00:05:30.260
So there are similar findings in terms of looking at time to VGPR. So you can see overall for the

00:05:30.260 --> 00:05:36.240
whole population, the median time to VGPR was 5.8 months, but there is certainly a difference in the

00:05:36.240 --> 00:05:41.620
curves for all three of the next charts that you can see there when looking at BTKI exposed,

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:47.740
CXCR4 mutated, and TP53 mutated, with a difference in the time to achieving that VGPR

00:05:47.740 --> 00:05:50.120
for each of those three different populations.

00:05:53.620 --> 00:05:58.780
Did very much clinically benefit from this therapy, though. As you can see, a significant

00:05:58.780 --> 00:06:05.400
drop in the IgM when patients were treated. Hemoglobin improved nicely, and we also saw a big

00:06:05.400 --> 00:06:09.460
reduction in the amount of disease in the bone marrow. So that differs from what we see with just

00:06:09.460 --> 00:06:15.400
a BTK inhibitor alone. So we were getting cell death and eradication of most of the disease in

00:06:15.400 --> 00:06:22.680
many cases. The progression-free survival at 12 months is 94%. You can see the safety profile here.

00:06:23.600 --> 00:06:29.660
We did see some cytopenias, including mostly neutropenia, which responded to growth factor in

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:35.700
most cases, although some patients did need dose reduction. And from an infection perspective,

00:06:36.180 --> 00:06:42.340
URIs were the most common and typically grade 2 or lower, and patients overall seemed to have

00:06:42.340 --> 00:06:52.160
tolerated this quite well. So in general, with the 15 patients at the time of this data collection

00:06:53.580 --> 00:07:00.000
of the VGPR-CR, the study met its endpoint. Although we do see prior exposure to BTK inhibitors

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:07.760
and the presence of a CX04 or TP53 mutation affect the time to achieving a VGPR and the

00:07:07.760 --> 00:07:12.740
ability to achieve a VGPR better. And I think an important thing we'll have to follow up on this is

00:07:12.740 --> 00:07:18.800
how long do patients maintain their response after coming off of treatment? Thank you very much.
